channel.title: If you change the cache on a client, does that change the deob?
channel.description:
I was argueing about this with someone.
He says that clients eg: bluurs that load 377 caches, are 377 clients.
Simply tell me this, IS BLUURS CLIENT A 317 [b]CLIENT[/b] OR A 377 [b]CLIENT[/b]?

item.title: If you change the cache on a client, does that change the deob?
item.dc:creator: @moparisthebest Moparisthebest
item.description:
@moparisthebest wrote:

The cache being loaded has nothing to do with the actual version the client (deob), because the version of the client determines which protocol the client uses. A 317 client will only connect to a 317 server, regardless of whether it loads a 317, 377, 508, or whatever version of the cache.

item.title: If you change the cache on a client, does that change the deob?
item.dc:creator: @primadude Primadude
item.description:
@primadude wrote:

No, the client defines what server it can connect to.

This value is sent from the client to the server:

aClass30_Sub2_Sub2_847.method399(317);

Then it is received by the server by using:

inStream.readUnsignedWord()

Which should return the value 317.

item.title: If you change the cache on a client, does that change the deob?
item.dc:creator: @T3arful T3arful
item.description:
@T3arful wrote:

[quote=“DemisePking, post:13, topic:330917”][quote author=T3arful link=topic=427289.msg3137862#msg3137862 date=1267218626]
The cache doesn’t define what server it can connect to, the packets within the client define that.

As in if you dump from a 525 cache you know it wont connect to a 317 if you put it into the cache folder

That’s because the clients loaders haven’t been configured to load that type of cache.
[/quote]

EXACTLY. thus the client is defined by the cache.[/quote]
No that is not what I’m saying. A 317 deob loading a 377 cache doesn’t make that client 377 as it still has all the 317 packets in the client.

What I’m saying is, is the packets within the client define what type of server it connects to, sure you can change them and configure them to a higher revision but it still makes the client a 317 one.
